metadata.name: Other ways #114
metadata.description:
Inspired by Paul Klee’s painting « Highways and byways », « Other ways » propose to build your own and unique generative painting.

7 features, including 4 main styles, 8 color palettes, 5 different parameters of the generative process.


Please note that the preview image is more saturated than the real token due to fxhash GPU management.

In Open Live window, press « s » to save the current image.
To get a High Resolution Image : press « r » to change the resolution for high definition, the image will reload and you can then use « s » to save the image (you can change DP in the URL to  a greater value for an even larger resolution in case you want to print it big).
This project is dimensionless, the Preview and OpenLive images are the same.

This artwork was created using p5js and scribble.

TidallyDisruptedStar. Paris. Jan 2022.

twitter : @TidallyD

metadata.name: Geologic #171
metadata.description:
This series was born from a desire to depict imagined landscapes from literal building 'blocks', and the fundamental concepts of stone, sea, and sky.

Each scene pairs a subtle nod to geological processes with the fleeting mood unveiled by weather and time of day.

metadata.name: Cartwheel #44
metadata.description:
A generative piece painting a playful composition with a huge cartwheel on the center and partially overlapping shapes around it. 

Very tiny strokes are first applied in the background to give a nice texture. A swoosh with a broader brush in the background gives the cartwheel a dynamic feel. 

Features 13 different colour palettes.

Hit 's' to save a frame as PNG.

Hit 'h' to save a 3000x3000px image for printing. Recommended size for print is about 25x25cm. Nice and cute.

metadata.name: Segments #476
metadata.description:
A continuous flowing motion of segmented cubes.

There is 5 routes for variations which is chosen by the 'Animation Type' variable. Each route then has it's own way to produce variety based on the random values injected into each.

Routes available (each is a type of noise used to change the animation of the cubes):
1. Waveform
2. Cellular
3. Voronoise
4. Polka Dots
5. Layers

Each route then has between 5 to 11 variables that will change the outcome of the overall look.

metadata.name: Esagoni #121
metadata.description:
A piece stepping away from control and leaning into minimalism, there are several factors at play to make your Esagoni unique. Both of the two hexagon colors are a random RGB value, at various luminosities.

The root of separation chooses which color takes the lead, between 1-100, 50 being evenly distributed.

The separation between the two colors can vary from 0-100, 0 is a 1% chance.

Modifiers can be either Circular or Hexagonal.

The scale of the hexagons on the grid varies from 1-100.

There is a 10% chance of a monochrome Esagoni, 5% respectively to both "Black on White" and "White on Black."


This piece can also be changed to infinite resolutions, for any frame or screen you'd like to display it on.

In live view, press:

'w' to view in 16:9

't' to view in 8x10

's' to view in 1x1

'f' to adapt to your own screen size

Double-click to save image

Enjoy :)

metadata.name: ASCII-SCAPE #18
metadata.description:
ASCII-SCAPE

Like for many others growing up during the 1980s & 90s, my very first hands-on encounter with actual computer graphics (outside of games) was in the form of "textmode" and its various alphanumeric characters and other symbols available on the 8bit home computers of that period. These machines were perfectly capable of producing fairly high-resolution & multi-color graphics (all relative), yet most systems booted into an interactive prompt with the so-called textmode as de-facto standard environment, providing a level, if also limited, playing field for the creation of text-based graphics from a patchwork of characters & symbols of a predefined font (system or custom). As is so often the case, limitation is the mother of invention and the regular, monospaced grid and standardized set of characters quickly encouraged an entire subculture of specialized designers & artists to emerge (which is currently being re-discovered & remixed by younger generations), applying & showcasing their creativity (with often surprisingly ingenious skills) in the form of game designs, user interfaces, disk mags, demoscene productions, competitions, flyers, BBSes and even various early Web designs of the mid/late 90s.

ASCII-SCAPE is an attempted non-nostalgic homage to these roots & culture. It is also a textmode-only (no canvas!) rework of my previous piece C-SCAPE. It combines my love of cellular automata with the stripped back aesthetics & limitations of using only text as representation medium of these co-evolving generative systems. It required an almost complete rewrite & re-curation of various elements: 1200+ new handpicked rule combinations, 32 character sets, 40 color themes, new relationships & biases to better manage the resulting textures, densities and contrast.

Although technically not strictly "ASCII" (an actual standard, but also a popular shorthand for "text only"), the entire simulation only uses various Unicode characters and the beautiful Iosevka open source typeface by Renzhi Li aka Belleve Invis.

Like its parent C-SCAPE, this project is dynamic and evolves indefinitely. It's best viewed on non-mobile devices, where there's a decent horizontal resolution to provide sufficient simulation space. Please see the C-SCAPE project description for further details. There's no graphical export feature, but output can be captured into an UTF-8 plain text file (max. 100k lines/generations).

The following keyboard shortcuts are available:

- space : toggle simulation updates (pause/play)
- r : randomize environment
- x : start/stop recording
- f : toggle scroll speed (fast/slow)

metadata.name: Mina #61
metadata.description:
A generative series of a-symmetric compositions.

Mina is a search for new textures created by combining 3 colors with 3 different mathematical equations.

Observe how Mina blends and creates its textures in time.

Probabilities;

- 18 color palettes.

- 2 background colors.

- 4 line placements.

- 14 different compositions, most of them have variations.


Made with p5.js

Ilgın İçözü, December 2021

The corrosive texture marks the temporal dimension as the main element.

- 7 patterns;

metadata.name: FX(T)RASH #35
metadata.description:
Imagine having Van Gogh's ear in a little box, getting your grubby hands on Banksy's stencils or Zancan's plotter! Well, here's something just as awesome - This is your chance to collect some trash straight from the King of Trash Art himself, Robness!

---

NOR44 & ROBNESS V2 JOIN FORCES TO CREATE A SPECIAL GENERATIVE PROJECT IN HONOR OF THE SECOND #TEZTRASH EVENT ON 12/21/22.  TEZTRASH IS A TEZOS COMMUNITY DAY WHEN THE CRYPTONATIVE ART MOVEMENT #TRASHART AND TRASH ART IN GENERAL IS CELEBRATED.  THE PREVIOUS TEZTRASH EVENT WAS A MONUMENTAL HIT ON TWITTER AND THIS TIME AROUND WE'VE DECIDED TO CONCOCT AN EPIC GENERATIVE DROP WHILST KEEPING THE TRASH ART ETHOS EMBEDDED IN THE WORK. HERE WE PLAY WITH THE NOTION OF 'TRASHING JPEGS' AND REINSERTING A PHYSICAL YET GENERATIVE REPRESENTATION OF THAT IDEA. ENJOY AND HAPPY TEZTRASH 2.0 DAY!

---

This generative artwork is composed of many layers of pre-rendered images with code utilized to stylize as well as randomly position, rotate and scale these elements, creating potentially infinite unique compositions resembling real-world outputs from a Photocopier/Copy Machine that's seen better days.
